# make a new column so we have the repeatable names for the genes and therefore cluster which ARFs, AFBs and IAAs have greater impact for tissues of interest.
data_expr_4pca <- expr_data %>% 
  mutate(Family = str_extract(expr_data$names, "At.*" )) %>% 
  mutate(Class = str_extract(expr_data$names,  "At.*" ))

# Also want to create a class column to try to plot circles that represents each family and their contributions to PCA

Each data point in our PCA dataset is plotted here in its coordinates from Principal component 1 and 2. This two linear combination of all the variables retrieved in by the PCA analysis accounts for most of the variability in our data. The ellipse drawn represents a 95% interval for each Class which helps us seeing the variability for each class and also demarcate where the majority of gene expression are. Genes that are clustered inside this ellipses are likely to be great candidates for rapid canopy cover development since there expression in its majority are positively correlated among tissues. Highly correlated gene expression cluster together!
